snippet.textDisplay:
Novak Djokovic’s Covid-19 katzenjammer: Having one’s Cake and Still Eating it
Any government’s inactivity in the face of a pandemic comes with consequences; it can be deadly. Hence a good reason the government takes all necessary measures to halt the spread of coronavirus and minimise infections and deaths, which are running in millions. Since we are living in a democratic world, individuals are free to decide whether they want to get vaccinated or not. But that decision has consequences as well. The idea of having one's cake and still eating it is where some might disagree with Novak Djokovic. Agreed he is anti-vaccination; that decision comes with repercussions; it must not be to the detriment of others or other countries' rules. For sure, Mr Djokovic did not go to Australia to help the government extinguish the wildfire or build a railway line for Australians. No. He is there for business. Yes, to make money. He is the favourite to win close to $4.5 million out of the AUD 75 million in prize money budgeted for the 2022 Australian Open. And, of course, Novak Djokovic wants to prolong his title bid and surpass Nadal and Roger Federer's 20 grand slams. He is chasing his career dream to become the most decorated tennis star in the world. A good reason to be law-abiding, isn't it? Being opposed to vaccination is one thing; breaking a country's law in the process of trying to achieve your dream, polish your career and enrich yourself comfortably is something else. Has Novak Djokovic ever thought about this?
